Coronavirus Questions and Answers forTri-Creek School Corporation Operations

The current spread of Coronavirus is an ever-changing situation. The following questions and answers are provided using the best information available at the time. As the situation changes, there may be more questions and the answers provided may change, too. 

Slowing the spread of Coronavirus is of great importance. Please refer to the guidance from the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) on prevention steps to take. For timely information on Coronavirus, you may want to sign up for e-mail updates from the Indiana State Department of Health.

Important Highlights - 

To ensure our students and staff members are as safe and healthy as possible, we are monitoring the Coronavirus spread. We will maintain contact with the health department advisors and will continue to communicate with parents during this evolving situation.
Our cleaning procedures have been intensified to help ensure that our schools are as clean as possible.
There are no confirmed cases of Coronavirus in any of our schools, in Lake County, or in adjacent counties.
Our schools will continue to remain open unless directed otherwise by the Lake County Health Department.
If there are other questions about school operations affected by Coronavirus, please read the remainder of this document. If you have a question that is not addressed below, please submit your question to CoronavirusQuestion@tricreek.k12.in.us. To continue to share information, responses to questions will be added to this document instead of responding to each individual email. If you have specific questions about your child, please contact your child’s principal.


Will our schools close?
The Lake County Health Department recommends closing schools when there is a student or staff member with a confirmed case of Coronavirus. At this time, there are no confirmed cases of Coronavirus in our schools, and there are no confirmed cases in Lake County or in adjacent counties.

What would cause our schools to close?
If there is one confirmed case in one of our schools, all schools will close. A belief that a student or staff member has been exposed to Coronavirus or may have symptoms associated with Coronavirus is not a reason to close our schools.

How long would our schools be closed?
The closure will last for at least 14 calendar days.

Will schools be closed for 14 days after spring break like some colleges and universities are doing?
There are no plans to close schools after spring break unless there is a confirmed case of Coronavirus in a student or staff member.

If schools are closed, what will happen with athletics and other extra-curricular activities?
If schools are closed, all other activities will be canceled.

Can athletes still practice or engage in conditioning activities if school is closed?
Unlike closing school for inclement weather, closing schools because of Coronavirus is done to help reduce the spread of the virus. To further help reduce the spread of the virus, no practices or conditioning activities will take place if school is closed.

What is the purpose of closing schools?
Some experts say schools should not be closed for COVID-19 unless there is active transmission in the community. "Just like with the flu, we would not close the school unless we know that there is a lot of transmission going on in the community," said Krys Johnson, an epidemiologist at the Temple University College of Public Health. "I think that should still be our marker here." In this case, the reason for closing schools has less to do with preventing the spread of coronavirus among children (who aren't hit hard by the virus), and more to do with preventing the spread to parents, grandparents, teachers, and adult staff, who may be at risk for more serious infections, Johnson said.

Would we have e-learning days if school is closed?
We would start with three e-learning days and then evaluate how effective those days were for students and parents. If students and parents were able to effectively engage in those days, then we would continue with additional days. If at some point, e-learning days are not effective or overly burdensome, we would simply switch to days of no school.

Would we have to make up days if we don’t use e-learning days?
On March 12, 2020, Governor Holcomb announced that schools would be provided with twenty (20) waiver days to use at the discretion of the school corporation. 

What happens if a student comes in contact with someone outside of school who has Coronavirus?
A student coming in contact with someone who has Coronavirus does not mean the student will contract the virus. However, it is advisable for the student’s parents to contact their health-care provider for guidance. Also, a parent may self-impose a 14-day quarantine. Students must have a documented recommendation from a health-care provider. If a parent chooses to self-quarantine, we ask that the parent contact his/her child’s principal so a learning plan with virtual lessons (Google Classroom or Echo) can be developed to help continue the child’s education as best as possible during the quarantine period.

How will a student’s attendance record be affected if a parent chooses to quarantine his or her child?
Since the student would not be present at school when school is in session, the student would be counted as absent. 

As a parent, I am worried about my child catching Coronavirus at school. Can I keep my child home even if he or she has not come in contact with someone who has the virus?
State law requires students to be in school each day that school is in session. If a student is not ill or the student does not have a medical condition preventing the student from attending school, the student should be in school. We understand a parent’s worry. At the same time, if there are a number of students whose parents keep them home, we cannot guarantee that our teachers will be able to provide learning activities for all absent students. Students who have a documented recommendation from a health-care provider will be provided with learning activities.

If my child has excessive absences, will there be consequences?
During this unprecedented time, we will suspend our usual attendance intervention procedures such as referral to the Department of Child Services, Lowell Town, or the assignment of disciplinary consequences. We will evaluate a student’s attendance history on a case-by-case basis.

Will seniors still graduate on time if school is closed?
We do not foresee anything that would stop seniors from graduating on time as long as they were already on track for graduating.

Will the date for graduation change?
We do not anticipate changing graduation. Parents and students have already made plans, and we would not want those to be changed.

Will high school students still be able to earn their credits even if school is closed for 14 days?
Yes.

Will high school students who have a work-study job still be able to go to work if school is closed?
Yes, unless the employer prohibits the student from reporting to work.

Have extra-curricular activities been canceled?
The school corporation has not canceled any activities within the school corporation at this time. Home athletic contests, practices, and performances are still occurring as scheduled. Events such as P.T.O. meetings, booster club meetings, etc. can continue to occur since students are not in school when those events take place. Outside organizations have canceled activities in which our students participate. Those organizations are ISSMA, Special Olympics, and evGrand Prix.

Will activities occurring in school where large crowds gather be cancelled?

Will study trips still take place?
Even if school is in session, study trips will be postponed indefinitely to reduce the community spread of Coronavirus. If a new date for the trip cannot be secured, we will request a refund from the organization/destination. If a refund cannot be obtained, the school or school corporation will not be able to provide compensation.

Will guests be permitted in our schools?
The safety and health of our students, staff, and guests is very important. To help preserve everyone’s health, the admittance of guests into our schools during the school day will be regulated. Events where there typically would be a large number of guests, such as award programs, may still occur, but guests will not be admitted. Other events, such as Grandparents Day, will not occur.
 
What is being done to make sure our schools are sanitary?
School nurses and staff are working with students to promote good hygiene (handwashing) to keep everyone healthy and safe.
The custodial staff has enhanced sanitation in high-touch areas to ensure our schools receive a thorough cleaning every day.
In addition to routine cleaning, the nurse’s office in each school is receiving an intensified cleaning to ensure as healthful of an environment as possible.
Our school buses are receiving additional cleaning with disinfectant spray.
The food service staff is exchanging common-use serving utensils frequently, sanitizing flat surfaces during lunch service, and reinforcing the use of proper practices to reduce illness.
We have inventoried our supply of hand soap, paper towels, and cleaning supplies to ensure we have an ample supply. 
Communication with the Lake County Health Department has been established, and we will continue to be in contact to ensure the safety of our students and staff.
Students may bring hand sanitizer to use as needed throughout the school day.

Will students or staff members who travel out of the country be quarantined upon return?
The Tri-Creek School Corporation does not authorize or sponsor study trips outside the continental United States. If students or staff members choose to travel abroad, the decision to quarantine will be made by appropriate state or federal officials who monitor travel at airports, seaports, and other locations.

Will community events scheduled to take place in our schools be canceled?
If our schools are closed, community events that were planned for our schools will be canceled. If our schools remain open, the decision to cancel community events scheduled to take place in our schools will be made by the event organizers. Additionally, according to Governor Holcomb’s announcement on March 12, there can be no gatherings in excess of 250 people.

Should we clean our MacBooks and/or iPads?
To help contain the spread of the Coronavirus, we have already enhanced our cleaning procedures, especially of high-touch areas. Students and parents can further the safety efforts by cleaning their MacBook and/or iPads and cases following the cleaning instructions from Apple.
